Reproducible Research: Peer Assessment 2

1. Title: Research Study on Impact of Storms and Severe Weather Events on Public Health and Economy

2. Synopsis

In this research study, we have analyzed the impact of storms and other severe weather events on public health and the economy using data from the U.S. National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration’s (NOAA) storm database with events collected from 1950 - 2011. There are two research questions addressed by this study: 1. Across the United States, which types of events (as indicated in the EVTYPE variable) are most harmful with respect to the population health (i.e., highest mortality rates); 2. Across the United States, which types of events have caused the greatest economic consequences (i.e., highest estimated property damage). The top 3 severe weather events in the U.S. from 1991 - 2011 causing injuries are Tornado, Flood, and Excessive Heat. The top 3 severe weather events in the U.S. from 1991 - 2011 causing fatalities are Excessive Heat, Tornado, and Flash Flood. The top 3 severe weather events in the U.S. from 1991 - 2011 causing crop damage as a measure of economic consequence are Drought, Flooding, and River Flooding. The top 3 severe weather events in the U.S. from 1991 - 2011 causing property damage are Tornados, Flash Floods, and TSTM Wind.

3.6.2 Transformation:Set property and crop damage variables to a numeric value based on exponent. Replace invalid expressions with a numeric value of 0.Both PROPDMGEXP and CROPDMGEXP columns contain a multiplier for each observation for example where we have Hundred (H), Thousand (K), Million (M) and Billion (B).

# Transformation function 
transform <- function (fData = smallData, f1, fexp) {
fData[(fData[,fexp] == "+"), f1] <- 0
fData[(fData[,fexp] == "-"), f1] <- 0
fData[(fData[,fexp] == "?"), f1] <- 0

fData[(fData[,fexp] ==  ""),  f1] <- fData[(fData[,fexp] ==  ""),  f1]  * 1e+00
fData[(fData[,fexp] == "0"),  f1] <- fData[(fData[,fexp] == "0"),  f1]  * 1e+00
fData[(fData[,fexp] == "1"),  f1] <- fData[(fData[,fexp] == "1"),  f1]  * 1e+01
fData[(fData[,fexp] == "2"),  f1] <- fData[(fData[,fexp] == "2"),  f1]  * 1e+02
fData[(fData[,fexp] == "3"),  f1] <- fData[(fData[,fexp] == "3"),  f1]  * 1e+03
fData[(fData[,fexp] == "4"),  f1] <- fData[(fData[,fexp] == "4"),  f1]  * 1e+04
fData[(fData[,fexp] == "5"),  f1] <- fData[(fData[,fexp] == "5"),  f1]  * 1e+05
fData[(fData[,fexp] == "6"),  f1] <- fData[(fData[,fexp] == "6"),  f1]  * 1e+06
fData[(fData[,fexp] == "7"),  f1] <- fData[(fData[,fexp] == "7"),  f1]  * 1e+07
fData[(fData[,fexp] == "8"),  f1] <- fData[(fData[,fexp] == "8"),  f1]  * 1e+08
fData[(fData[,fexp] == "9"),  f1] <- fData[(fData[,fexp] == "9"),  f1]  * 1e+09

fData[(toupper(fData[,fexp]) == "H"),  f1] <- fData[(toupper(fData[,fexp]) == "H"),  f1]  * 1e+02
fData[(toupper(fData[,fexp]) == "K"),  f1] <- fData[(toupper(fData[,fexp]) == "K"),  f1]  * 1e+03
fData[(toupper(fData[,fexp]) == "M"),  f1] <- fData[(toupper(fData[,fexp]) == "M"),  f1]  * 1e+06
fData[(toupper(fData[,fexp]) == "B"),  f1] <- fData[(toupper(fData[,fexp]) == "B"),  f1]  * 1e+09
return (fData)
}
dataSet <-transform(smallData, which(colnames(smallData) == "PROPDMG"), which(colnames(smallData) == "PROPDMGEXP"))
dataSet <-transform(smallData, which(colnames(smallData) == "CROPDMG"), which(colnames(smallData) == "CROPDMGEXP"))
  • After processing, there are 740794 rows and 9 columns in the dataset.

4.2 Results of the data analysis to addresses the following questions:

4.2.1 Across the United States, which types of events (as indicated in the EVTYPE variable) are most harmful with respect to population health? The results are:

gg1 <- ggplot(sumInjuries, aes(EVTYPE, INJURIES)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 0.5) + 
  scale_y_continuous("Number of Injuries") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust = 1)) +
  labs(title = "Severe Weather Events\n from 1991-2011\n Across the U.S.\n Causing Injuries\n ", x = "Severe Weather Type")

gg2 <- ggplot(sumFatalities, aes(EVTYPE, FATALITIES)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 0.5) + 
  scale_y_continuous("Number of Fatalities") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust = 1)) +
  labs(title = "Severe Weather Events\n from 1991-2011\n Across the U.S.\n Causing Fatalities\n ", x = "Severe Weather Type")

grid.arrange (gg1, gg2, ncol=2, padding=3)

The top 3 severe weather events in the U.S. from 1991 - 2011 causing injuries are Tornado, Flood, and Excessive Heat. The top 3 severe weather events in the U.S. from 1991 - 2011 causing fatalities are Excessive Heat, Tornado, and Flash Flood.

4.2.2 Across the United States, which types of events have the greatest economic consequences? The results are:

gg1 <- ggplot(sumCropDamage, aes(EVTYPE, CROPDMG)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 0.5) + 
  scale_y_continuous("Crop Damage in US Dollars") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust = 1)) +

The top 3 severe weather events in the U.S. from 1991 - 2011 causing crop damage as a measure of economic consequence are Drought, Flooding, and River Flooding. The top 3 severe weather events in the U.S. from 1991 - 2011 causing property damage are Tornados, Flash Floods, and TSTM Wind.
